  "antony2023|claro2016": "SOURCE 1: Antony (2022). Antony's 2022 discussion paper argues that resilience may be supported across nested environmental layers; it is a conceptual application, not an empirical demonstration that resilience can be taught. Evidence type: Discussion paper using Bronfenbrenner's theory. Evidence limit: No empirical sample; the paper reviews ideas and implications for childhood resilience. It argues that resilience may be supported or taught across nested settings; it does not empirically demonstrate that an intervention taught resilience. SOURCE 2: Claro, Paunesku, and Dweck (2016). Mindset and achievement can be studied empirically, which keeps the idea grounded in evidence rather than slogan. Evidence type: Observational analysis of national Chilean student data. Evidence limit: Tenth-grade students in Chile's national education dataset. Mindset, family income, and achievement were associated; the observational design does not show that mindset caused achievement or removed poverty-related barriers. Comparison question: what becomes visible when Context, Culture & Social Ecology is placed beside Mindset & Beliefs About Ability, and which link is a course interpretation rather than a source finding? Keep the methods separate: this comparison helps you reason across sources; it does not mean either source tested, confirmed, or caused the other source's claim.",
  "antony2023|jadmiko2024": "SOURCE 1: Antony (2022). Antony's 2022 discussion paper argues that resilience may be supported across nested environmental layers; it is a conceptual application, not an empirical demonstration that resilience can be taught. Evidence type: Discussion paper using Bronfenbrenner's theory. Evidence limit: No empirical sample; the paper reviews ideas and implications for childhood resilience. It argues that resilience may be supported or taught across nested settings; it does not empirically demonstrate that an intervention taught resilience. SOURCE 2: Jadmiko, Mustika, and Bashiruddin (2024). Reflective-writing and resilience scores increased after the workshops in this 57-student one-group study; the design does not establish causation. Evidence type: One-group pre-test and post-test study. Evidence limit: 57 nursing students who completed reflective-writing workshops. Scores were higher after the workshops, but without a comparison group the study cannot isolate the workshop as the cause or establish generalizability. Comparison question: what becomes visible when Context, Culture & Social Ecology is placed beside Reflection & Metacognition and Resilience as Process, and which link is a course interpretation rather than a source finding? Keep the methods separate: this comparison helps you reason across sources; it does not mean either source tested, confirmed, or caused the other source's claim.",
  "antony2023|kamarulzaman2026": "SOURCE 1: Antony (2022). Antony's 2022 discussion paper argues that resilience may be supported across nested environmental layers; it is a conceptual application, not an empirical demonstration that resilience can be taught. Evidence type: Discussion paper using Bronfenbrenner's theory. Evidence limit: No empirical sample; the paper reviews ideas and implications for childhood resilience. It argues that resilience may be supported or taught across nested settings; it does not empirically demonstrate that an intervention taught resilience. SOURCE 2: Kamarulzaman and Ibrahim (2026). Across three journal cycles, researchers observed seven critical-thinking dispositions and interpreted changes in the writing as deeper engagement; this was a qualitative pattern, not a causal test. Evidence type: Qualitative longitudinal journal analysis. Evidence limit: 135 journals from 45 Malaysian undergraduates across three collection points, using a convenience sample. The study identifies and interprets patterns in writing; it does not show that journaling caused stronger critical thinking or performance. Comparison question: what becomes visible when Context, Culture & Social Ecology is placed beside Reflection & Metacognition, and which link is a course interpretation rather than a source finding? Keep the methods separate: this comparison helps you reason across sources; it does not mean either source tested, confirmed, or caused the other source's claim.",
  "antony2023|nas2025": "SOURCE 1: Antony (2022). Antony's 2022 discussion paper argues that resilience may be supported across nested environmental layers; it is a conceptual application, not an empirical demonstration that resilience can be taught. Evidence type: Discussion paper using Bronfenbrenner's theory. Evidence limit: No empirical sample; the paper reviews ideas and implications for childhood resilience. It argues that resilience may be supported or taught across nested settings; it does not empirically demonstrate that an intervention taught resilience. SOURCE 2: Nas, Taytas, and Vangolu (2025). In this sample of academics, perseverance, self-compassion, psychological flexibility, and life satisfaction were positively related; the proposed indirect paths are statistical associations, not proof of causation. Evidence type: Cross-sectional questionnaire study with structural-equation modelling. Evidence limit: 305 academics in Türkiye measured at one time point. The paths are consistent with the authors' model but remain associations; the study cannot establish mediation over time or causal effects. Comparison question: what becomes visible when Context, Culture & Social Ecology is placed beside Well-Being & Self-Compassion and Resilience as Process, and which link is a course interpretation rather than a source finding? Keep the methods separate: this comparison helps you reason across sources; it does not mean either source tested, confirmed, or caused the other source's claim.",
