  "richardson2011|yeager-dweck2020": "SOURCE 1: Richardson (2011). Richardson's metatheory maps disruption and several possible forms of reintegration; it is a conceptual model, not evidence that every hard period moves toward growth. Evidence type: Conceptual metatheory article. Evidence limit: No student intervention sample; the article applies a metatheory to rehabilitation and medicine. It maps several possible forms of reintegration and does not show that disruption necessarily causes growth or follows one sequence for every person. SOURCE 2: Yeager and Dweck (2020). Growth mindset is a useful but bounded idea: capacity can grow with the right support, but belief alone does not overcome every obstacle. Evidence type: Narrative review and controversy analysis. Evidence limit: Synthesizes multiple studies and debates rather than reporting one new intervention sample. It supports a bounded account of growth mindset and explicitly rejects belief-alone and blame-the-student interpretations. Comparison question: what becomes visible when Resilience as Process is placed beside Mindset & Beliefs About Ability, and which link is a course interpretation rather than a source finding? Keep the methods separate: this comparison helps you reason across sources; it does not mean either source tested, confirmed, or caused the other source's claim.",
