   "abstract": "Owen argues that much of contemporary resilience psychology has clear roots in ancient Greek and Roman practical philosophy, particularly Stoic, Cynic, and Epicurean thought, even though that lineage is rarely examined. He reviews modern resilience research alongside these older systems, which trained practitioners to insulate themselves from life's ups and downs and to become self sufficient in their happiness. He introduces what he calls eudaimonic resilience, the ability to flourish across all circumstances, and suggests that connecting the two fields enriches both.",
   "coreIdea": "Owen proposes connections between contemporary resilience psychology and ancient practical philosophy. This is a historical and conceptual argument that invites research, not evidence that one routine causes resilience.",
